1
00:00:41,698 --> 00:00:43,127
Can I play?

2
00:00:43,234 --> 00:00:45,721
Do you have any marbles?

3
00:00:45,795 --> 00:00:47,386
Yep.

4
00:00:49,089 --> 00:00:50,616
OK.

5
00:00:50,689 --> 00:00:51,800
Thanks.

6
00:00:51,872 --> 00:00:53,247
You're welcome.

7
00:00:53,312 --> 00:00:54,622
So, what's your name?

8
00:00:54,689 --> 00:00:56,118
Louis. Yours?

9
00:00:56,193 --> 00:00:57,566
Alan.

10
00:00:57,633 --> 00:00:59,900
You're not from around here,
are you?

11
00:00:59,966 --> 00:01:03,282
No. I'm here with my parents
for the day.

12
00:01:08,317 --> 00:01:09,779
What?

13
00:01:09,885 --> 00:01:11,925
What's over there?

14
00:01:23,227 --> 00:01:25,431
Don't do that. We're not
even allowed to be here.

15
00:01:33,433 --> 00:01:34,961
Come on.

16
00:01:35,034 --> 00:01:36,594
Wait for me.

17
00:01:45,942 --> 00:01:48,114
Let's go back down.

18
00:01:48,184 --> 00:01:49,938
Nope.

19
00:01:51,318 --> 00:01:52,430
Don't!

20
00:02:05,173 --> 00:02:06,285
Alan, don't!

21
00:02:11,986 --> 00:02:14,059
See? That wasn't so bad.

22
00:02:14,163 --> 00:02:15,536
Just don't look down.

23
00:02:19,122 --> 00:02:20,266
Louis!

24
00:02:22,672 --> 00:02:24,233
Come on.

25
00:02:31,342 --> 00:02:33,676
See? It's steady.

26
00:02:52,813 --> 00:02:54,787
- Louis!
- I can't move!

27
00:02:54,858 --> 00:02:56,451
Come on!

28
00:02:58,347 --> 00:03:01,826
Alan, help!

29
00:03:04,202 --> 00:03:06,144
Wait!

30
00:06:30,664 --> 00:06:32,518
Here it comes. Just relax.

31
00:06:32,583 --> 00:06:34,109
You're doing great now.

32
00:06:34,182 --> 00:06:36,996
All right.
Now, just a couple more seconds.

33
00:06:37,061 --> 00:06:38,916
Here it comes, sweetie.

34
00:06:38,981 --> 00:06:40,671
Just keep breathing.

35
00:06:40,741 --> 00:06:43,393
All right, the head's crowning.
Very good.

36
00:06:43,462 --> 00:06:44,770
Excellent. Here we go.

37
00:06:44,837 --> 00:06:46,364
One more big push, sweetie.

38
00:06:46,438 --> 00:06:48,771
That's it. Now breathe.

39
00:06:48,836 --> 00:06:50,690
It's coming.

40
00:06:50,756 --> 00:06:53,122
Push, push, push!

41
00:06:55,554 --> 00:06:57,244
Oh, here we go.

42
00:06:57,347 --> 00:07:00,193
We have a boy.

43
00:07:02,785 --> 00:07:04,639
Oh, is he OK?

44
00:07:04,705 --> 00:07:07,041
- He's perfect.
- He's fine. He's fine.

45
00:07:07,106 --> 00:07:08,959
A beautiful son.

46
00:07:09,025 --> 00:07:11,871
Beautiful. He's beautiful.

47
00:07:17,983 --> 00:07:19,989
- Are we OK?
- He's fine, honey.

48
00:07:20,062 --> 00:07:22,484
- He's beautiful.
- Oh, he's perfect.

49
00:07:22,558 --> 00:07:25,111
Congratulations, Dad.

50
00:07:25,182 --> 00:07:26,874
Here he comes.

51
00:07:26,942 --> 00:07:28,794
You did really well.

52
00:07:28,860 --> 00:07:33,084
Oh, hi. Oh, it's OK.

53
00:07:33,148 --> 00:07:36,280
Beautiful baby boy.
You did really well.

54
00:07:36,349 --> 00:07:38,715
He's got his eyes open.
He's looking at you.

55
00:07:38,812 --> 00:07:41,561
- What's his name?
- Danny.

56
00:07:58,775 --> 00:08:00,433
Danny.

57
00:08:00,504 --> 00:08:03,472
Danny, come here, sweetie.
Get away from the ants.

58
00:08:07,256 --> 00:08:09,141
See, we have the best-fed ants
in the neighborhood.

59
00:08:09,238 --> 00:08:10,581
Come on.

60
00:08:10,646 --> 00:08:12,305
Have to do that later.

61
00:08:12,375 --> 00:08:14,546
Jason, my guys took
your guy's gun.

62
00:08:14,614 --> 00:08:16,786
Can't.
It's attached to his leg. See?

63
00:08:16,853 --> 00:08:18,414
Oh, my God.

64
00:08:18,486 --> 00:08:20,656
That's me, man.

65
00:08:22,133 --> 00:08:23,377
That's me.

66
00:08:23,445 --> 00:08:25,812
Danny, play nice
with your brother.

67
00:08:25,877 --> 00:08:28,844
What's that music you're using?
I really dig it.

68
00:08:32,530 --> 00:08:35,628
Whatever it is,
it's terrific, man.

69
00:08:35,729 --> 00:08:37,868
It really...

70
00:08:37,971 --> 00:08:40,272
I don't know...

71
00:08:40,338 --> 00:08:42,509
suits his life somehow.

72
00:08:42,577 --> 00:08:44,998
So, Danny, you still drawing?

73
00:08:45,073 --> 00:08:46,187
Nope.

74
00:08:46,257 --> 00:08:49,672
No? Didn't you want to grow up
to be an artist?

75
00:08:52,016 --> 00:08:53,542
That's some
of the opening sequence.

76
00:08:53,614 --> 00:08:56,297
The rest needs
some fixes and tweaks.

77
00:08:56,367 --> 00:08:58,855
But right now, he's clocking in
at one hour and 40 minutes.

78
00:08:58,927 --> 00:09:00,781
Yeah, that's cool.

79
00:09:02,093 --> 00:09:04,264
I just wanted to have a look...

80
00:09:04,332 --> 00:09:05,826
before the Rememory tomorrow.

81
00:09:05,901 --> 00:09:07,428
You know.

82
00:09:07,533 --> 00:09:09,541
You've done a hell of a job
with him, Mr. Hakman.

83
00:09:09,645 --> 00:09:11,498
You've done
the son of a bitch right.

84
00:09:11,562 --> 00:09:13,090
You're welcome.

85
00:09:15,564 --> 00:09:17,319
I don't suppose...

86
00:09:17,387 --> 00:09:19,656
There was a fishing trip
when we were 13.

87
00:09:19,724 --> 00:09:21,216
Just Danny and I and Dad...

88
00:09:21,291 --> 00:09:23,428
- At the cape.
- Yes, that one.

89
00:09:23,498 --> 00:09:25,768
My God,
that day is still with me.

90
00:09:25,835 --> 00:09:28,071
You requested it specifically.
It's there.

91
00:09:28,137 --> 00:09:30,559
Well, I'll be off, then.

92
00:09:43,269 --> 00:09:46,499
Closing Zoe project
D. Monroe, rough cut 6.

93
00:09:49,542 --> 00:09:53,218
Opening D. Monroe, scene 127-Q.

94
00:09:53,285 --> 00:09:54,746
Jesus Christ!

95
00:09:54,821 --> 00:09:57,309
I told you to shut up!

96
00:09:57,381 --> 00:10:00,347
Danny! Danny, stop!

97
00:10:00,420 --> 00:10:02,753
You...

98
00:10:02,819 --> 00:10:05,949
You deserve this, bitch!

99
00:10:06,018 --> 00:10:07,479
No!

100
00:10:07,555 --> 00:10:10,751
No! God! Please... please...

101
00:10:10,851 --> 00:10:14,200
No! Stop! No! You're killing me!

102
00:10:15,489 --> 00:10:16,602
Stop!

103
00:10:19,426 --> 00:10:22,491
Scene 127-Q deleted.

104
00:10:32,447 --> 00:10:34,388
EYE Tech introduces...

105
00:10:34,462 --> 00:10:36,795
the ninth generation
of the Zoe implant...

106
00:10:36,861 --> 00:10:39,065
from our family to yours.

107
00:10:39,134 --> 00:10:41,173
Do you think
we'll be able to afford one?

108
00:10:41,245 --> 00:10:43,033
Yep.

109
00:10:43,133 --> 00:10:44,377
I hope so.

110
00:10:44,476 --> 00:10:48,786
Well, we can save.
It's worth it, I think.

111
00:11:06,010 --> 00:11:07,732
Excuse me.

112
00:11:35,733 --> 00:11:38,994
This girl was a complete wreck.

113
00:11:39,060 --> 00:11:41,907
Drinking, drugs,
in and out of schools.

114
00:11:41,973 --> 00:11:43,249
Then she turns 21...

115
00:11:43,316 --> 00:11:46,216
and she finds out
about her Zoe implant.

116
00:11:46,323 --> 00:11:48,657
Complete 180. She's born again.

117
00:11:48,722 --> 00:11:51,537
Her knowing that
someone would one day watch...

118
00:11:51,602 --> 00:11:55,856
transforms her into this kind,
gentle, loving person.

119
00:11:55,921 --> 00:11:57,928
So, what happened?

120
00:11:58,001 --> 00:11:59,692
She committed suicide.

121
00:11:59,761 --> 00:12:01,769
Took a dive off her balcony...

122
00:12:01,842 --> 00:12:05,637
twenty-seven floors
straight onto her head.

123
00:12:05,711 --> 00:12:07,436
The implant
was instantly vaporized.

124
00:12:07,503 --> 00:12:10,185
Charming story, Hasan.
Please do go on.

125
00:12:10,255 --> 00:12:12,808
Alan!
This is a rare treat.

126
00:12:12,879 --> 00:12:14,188
Alan!

127
00:12:14,255 --> 00:12:16,589
Michael, this is Alan Hakman.

128
00:12:16,653 --> 00:12:17,733
- Hi.
- Hi.

129
00:12:17,838 --> 00:12:19,364
It's an honor to meet you.

130
00:12:19,470 --> 00:12:21,160
Mike is my new assistant.

131
00:12:21,262 --> 00:12:22,439
What happened to Eddie?

132
00:12:22,541 --> 00:12:25,159
Eddie freaked out on me.
Strung too tight.

133
00:12:25,229 --> 00:12:27,715
Hey, Alan, have you seen these?

134
00:12:27,788 --> 00:12:29,511
They are all over town.

135
00:12:29,579 --> 00:12:32,895
These anti-Zoe hippies always
seemed a little crazy to me.

136
00:12:32,972 --> 00:12:36,680
But now they just seem crazy.

137
00:12:36,747 --> 00:12:38,852
Listen...

138
00:12:38,923 --> 00:12:42,499
"It is not our place to see
through other people's eyes.

139
00:12:42,570 --> 00:12:46,660
"That is for God and God alone."

140
00:12:46,729 --> 00:12:49,630
Anyway, how's
the Monroe project coming?

141
00:12:49,703 --> 00:12:50,882
Fine.

142
00:12:50,985 --> 00:12:53,471
- Just fine?
- Just fine.

143
00:12:53,576 --> 00:12:56,161
Michael,
it's your great privilege...

144
00:12:56,232 --> 00:12:57,408
to meet this man.

145
00:12:57,478 --> 00:12:58,788
He's the best cutter in town.

146
00:12:58,854 --> 00:13:01,123
- Who's your assistant?
- I don't have an assistant.

147
00:13:01,190 --> 00:13:04,006
I have a friend that's looking
to get into the racket.

148
00:13:04,071 --> 00:13:06,144
I don't work with an assistant.

149
00:13:07,141 --> 00:13:08,668
You have
something for me, Thelma?

150
00:13:08,741 --> 00:13:09,951
Straight to business.

151
00:13:10,021 --> 00:13:12,804
I got a job last week
that I passed on...

152
00:13:12,870 --> 00:13:14,560
and I think
it's right up your alley.

153
00:13:14,629 --> 00:13:16,320
You know Charles Bannister?

154
00:13:16,389 --> 00:13:18,592
His widow
is looking for a cutter.

155
00:13:18,661 --> 00:13:19,868
Bannister, the EYE Tech lawyer?

156
00:13:19,938 --> 00:13:22,623
He was out jogging
and his heart collapsed.

157
00:13:22,722 --> 00:13:24,697
Wait a minute.
EYE Tech let that footage out?

158
00:13:24,803 --> 00:13:26,974
Jennifer Bannister
won the lawsuit against them...

159
00:13:27,043 --> 00:13:28,864
and claimed
her husband's implant.

160
00:13:28,930 --> 00:13:30,686
She insisted on having
her own cutter, too.

161
00:13:30,753 --> 00:13:32,575
And with good reason.

162
00:13:32,641 --> 00:13:34,049
We could have taken that job.

163
00:13:34,113 --> 00:13:35,673
After Caldwell,
our schedule is wide open.

164
00:13:35,745 --> 00:13:37,655
I don't like the ugly stuff.

165
00:13:37,729 --> 00:13:39,004
It gives me nightmares.

166
00:13:39,073 --> 00:13:41,723
And this pig Bannister...

167
00:13:41,792 --> 00:13:44,890
he's human garbage.

168
00:13:44,960 --> 00:13:48,602
I took one look at the footage
and sent it straight back.

169
00:13:48,671 --> 00:13:52,826
She only hired me because
you were busy with Monroe.

170
00:13:52,893 --> 00:13:54,420
It's you she really wants.

171
00:13:54,527 --> 00:13:56,380
- I'm available.
- Good.

172
00:13:56,446 --> 00:13:57,722
Our friend Alan...

173
00:13:57,790 --> 00:13:59,731
that's his specialty,
so to speak.

174
00:13:59,836 --> 00:14:02,552
If you can't bear
to look at it, he will.

175
00:14:02,621 --> 00:14:04,311
I'll tell her
you'll come by tomorrow.

176
00:14:04,380 --> 00:14:05,787
She'll be expecting you.

177
00:14:08,187 --> 00:14:09,593
We should actually go.

178
00:14:09,659 --> 00:14:11,348
Oh, yes.
Rememory is in two days...

179
00:14:11,419 --> 00:14:13,274
and we're still cutting picture.

180
00:14:13,339 --> 00:14:15,194
Goddamn last-minute jobs.

181
00:14:15,258 --> 00:14:17,625
Thelma, come on.
It keeps you young.

182
00:14:17,689 --> 00:14:19,379
Alan.

183
00:14:21,018 --> 00:14:22,392
Hasan.

184
00:14:22,458 --> 00:14:25,903
Oh, hey, Alan.
I've been working on...

185
00:14:26,008 --> 00:14:28,016
this new sorting program
for the Guillotine...

186
00:14:28,120 --> 00:14:30,990
and I would really love
to get your feedback on it.

187
00:14:31,095 --> 00:14:32,501
Maybe another time.

188
00:14:35,703 --> 00:14:37,907
Yeah, maybe some other time.

189
00:14:55,573 --> 00:14:57,427
Put it in archives very gently.

190
00:14:57,523 --> 00:14:58,668
- Sure.
- All right.

191
00:14:58,771 --> 00:15:01,257
Delila,
is suicide under self-help?

192
00:15:03,251 --> 00:15:04,495
What are you doing here?

193
00:15:04,563 --> 00:15:07,246
I just wanted to talk.

194
00:15:08,690 --> 00:15:10,097
I'm busy.

195
00:15:13,169 --> 00:15:16,299
Store's still open.
It's the 11:30 rush.

196
00:15:16,368 --> 00:15:18,572
Books are flying off the shelf.

197
00:15:24,622 --> 00:15:26,988
We close in 20 minutes.

198
00:15:35,852 --> 00:15:37,674
This is exciting.

199
00:15:37,741 --> 00:15:39,147
You've never had me over before.

200
00:15:39,212 --> 00:15:41,068
You've always
wanted to see my work.

201
00:15:41,134 --> 00:15:42,822
Well, you're always working.

202
00:15:42,891 --> 00:15:45,891
I'm curious about
what takes up all your time.

203
00:16:32,453 --> 00:16:34,174
Guillotine.

204
00:16:37,282 --> 00:16:40,097
You're like a mortician...

205
00:16:40,162 --> 00:16:41,723
or a priest...

206
00:16:43,201 --> 00:16:44,891
or a taxidermist.

207
00:16:44,960 --> 00:16:46,520
All of them.

208
00:16:48,224 --> 00:16:50,168
I mean...

209
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:54,006
you get to see life upon life.

210
00:16:54,079 --> 00:16:57,079
Most of us get only one,
if that.

211
00:16:58,624 --> 00:17:00,248
What are people's lives like?

212
00:17:00,319 --> 00:17:02,740
Do they make any sense?

213
00:17:02,815 --> 00:17:05,749
It all seems so massive
and so random.

214
00:17:05,822 --> 00:17:08,756
Have you ever been
to a Rememory?

215
00:17:08,861 --> 00:17:11,927
No. Well...

216
00:17:11,997 --> 00:17:13,720
Once, a few years ago.

217
00:17:13,789 --> 00:17:15,033
Whose?

218
00:17:16,763 --> 00:17:19,316
My ex-boyfriend.

219
00:17:19,388 --> 00:17:22,454
But I couldn't take it.
I didn't stay.

220
00:17:22,524 --> 00:17:23,898
Why not?

221
00:17:25,241 --> 00:17:27,130
Because it just wasn't...

222
00:17:28,761 --> 00:17:30,801
It wasn't him.

223
00:17:32,281 --> 00:17:35,127
And I wanted
to remember him my way.

224
00:17:36,631 --> 00:17:38,671
Sit down.

225
00:17:43,737 --> 00:17:45,230
Thank you.

226
00:18:38,286 --> 00:18:41,253
It's like
you read my mind, Alan.

227
00:18:41,326 --> 00:18:44,871
I have this recurring dream
where I'm aging backwards.

228
00:19:19,527 --> 00:19:21,119
Wow.

229
00:19:27,046 --> 00:19:29,215
What about all the bits
in between?

230
00:19:29,284 --> 00:19:30,658
It's a miniature.

231
00:19:30,725 --> 00:19:33,278
Concise, symmetrical.

232
00:19:33,349 --> 00:19:35,618
That's the way the world
looks to me...

233
00:19:35,685 --> 00:19:37,027
the way I see it.

234
00:19:38,275 --> 00:19:40,696
How do you do this?

235
00:19:40,771 --> 00:19:43,488
It's what I was meant to do.

236
00:19:43,554 --> 00:19:47,449
You were meant
to live your own life, too.

237
00:19:53,504 --> 00:19:55,392
- Hey.
- Hey.

238
00:20:09,726 --> 00:20:11,548
The house was big...

239
00:20:11,613 --> 00:20:14,001
enormous...

240
00:20:14,078 --> 00:20:15,802
like this one.

241
00:20:15,869 --> 00:20:18,291
We didn't care
whose house it was.

242
00:20:18,397 --> 00:20:22,423
It felt dangerous to be there.

243
00:20:22,524 --> 00:20:25,720
It felt exciting.

244
00:20:25,787 --> 00:20:28,089
I can see the grass.

245
00:20:28,157 --> 00:20:31,635
I can hear it
crunching beneath our feet.

246
00:20:31,706 --> 00:20:33,594
And then the sprinklers
came on...

247
00:20:33,659 --> 00:20:35,927
all around us...

248
00:20:35,994 --> 00:20:38,033
and we ran.

249
00:20:39,577 --> 00:20:42,359
I remember that
like it was yesterday.

250
00:20:46,073 --> 00:20:49,367
Do you recall any moments
with your daughter?

251
00:20:51,479 --> 00:20:53,901
This isn't long ago.

252
00:20:54,008 --> 00:20:56,821
We were watching Isabel
in a school talent show.

253
00:20:56,887 --> 00:21:00,017
She was wonderful that night.

254
00:21:00,085 --> 00:21:03,347
I think Charles and I
both felt...

255
00:21:03,414 --> 00:21:06,194
what an amazing thing
a family was.

256
00:21:06,260 --> 00:21:08,236
We felt it together.

257
00:21:09,717 --> 00:21:12,399
She was up there on that stage.

258
00:21:14,484 --> 00:21:17,517
Oh, goodness.

259
00:21:19,155 --> 00:21:20,714
Excuse me.

260
00:21:20,786 --> 00:21:23,404
I know this is very hard,
Mrs. Bannister...

261
00:21:23,505 --> 00:21:25,164
but it's important.

262
00:21:25,266 --> 00:21:27,722
It's the foundation
of a cutter's work.

263
00:21:27,826 --> 00:21:29,679
I need you and your family...

264
00:21:29,745 --> 00:21:32,462
to help me choose
those moments you want to keep.

265
00:21:33,744 --> 00:21:35,598
I won't be able to do
your husband justice...

266
00:21:35,663 --> 00:21:38,511
if I don't understand him
through you.

267
00:21:40,816 --> 00:21:43,433
I heard you were the best...

268
00:21:43,503 --> 00:21:46,918
that you would know
how to handle Charles.

269
00:21:48,622 --> 00:21:52,777
